<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Arhu:
[I]~[i]Since it isn't strictly a development issue[/i]~
Oh, that's no problem - actually everything that gives the developers food for thought or just encourages them... to work even harder, implement all our wishes, and upload mpegs and screenies once in a while, is at the right place over there.  ;)
Totally unrelated topics tend to be posted in "RPG Chat"...

btw, I've read the (longish) article. Reminds me of the latest D2 update (v1.08) - I've stopped playing D2 a long time ago, so I'm not affected by it, but honestly, making such severe gameplay changes that late after the game's release seems to be really awkward.
They should at least have let high level players re-distribute their skill points, the way BG2 does it if you import characters from the prequel. That, however, could be regarded as cheating, in regard to D2's gameplay. Besides, high level players propably have adopted to a certain playing style, and they would have had to reconsider their entire strategies.


From the article:
~[i]Imms also begin to care less and less about the PEOPLE on the mud, those who the mud was originally built to serve, and they begin to think more in terms of the CREATION[/i]~
I personally don't think that this is necessarily a bad thing, albeit it is not so hot for seriously wimped players. Nevertheless, it's best to focus on the creation [i]before[/i] a release, and maybe add a few gameplay [i]enhancing[/i] features later on.

~[i]If you had two knives, one dull and one sharp, would it not make better sense to make them equal by sharpening the dull one - not by blunting the sharp one?[/i]~
This could of course be changed to a "sharp knife" vs. a "insta-death laser rifle". Then changing the sharp knive to another insta-death laser rifle wouldn't make as much sense, since it would change the entire game philosophy and could possibly be worse than "sharp knife" vs. "dull knife".

Be that as it may, basically I'm all for (even belated) gameplay adjustments, as long as the players' needs are not entirely neglected. But I also think that the player's need don't always correspond with what he [i]thinks[/i] he needs . . .

[i]Meow...[/i]
Arhu[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
